ct line. Two firms form a partnership. These instances and many more like them dot today's business landscape. And yet, we understand little about the social dimension of these undertakings. Disentangling brokerage from network structure and building on his theoretical work regarding tertius iungens, David Obstfeld explains how actors with diverse interests, expertise, and skills leverage their personal and intellectual connections to create new ventures and products with extraordinary results.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBusiness networks. 0aProject management. 0aSocial networks. 0aSocial skills. 0aTechnological innovationsxManagement. 4abrokerage process. 4abrokerage. 4acreative projects. 4ainnovation. 4aknowledge articulation. 4asocial networks. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Organizational Behavior.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503603097zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503603097423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503603097.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles